^-|CP||va|4|AT|^b@2^*B38^*N. The best time to lead a short suit is with trump control. 
^C@2A-x-(x) or K-x-x are great trump holdings to lead from shortness. However, if ruffing will cost you a trump trick, leads from shortness with trump holdings such as J-10-x-x, Q-J-9-x or K-Q-9-x are counter productive.

^b@2^*B39^*N. When signaling encouragement with equal spot cards, signal with the higher or highest equal.
^C@2With A-9-8-7, signal encouragement with the 9 (which denies the 10). If you lazily signal with the 8, you are denying the 9! Some partners actually watch stuff like that.

^b@2^*B40^*N. When giving partner a ruff, the card you lead is suit preference telling partner which suit to return after the ruff.
^C@2The return of a relatively high spot card asks for a return in the higher ranking of the two remaining suits. 
^C@2A return of your lowest card asks for a return in the lower ranking of the two remaining suits. 
^C@2The return of a middle card is designed to drive partner crazy. It actually means you have no preference.

^b@2^*B41^*N. Before playing to the first trick, review the bidding and make sure you remember the opening lead.
^C@2Sometimes the opening lead is a small spot card and it is important to know exactly how small. If the opening leader later plays another small card in that suit, you really want to know whether it is a higher or lower card than the original lead. You really do!

^b@2^*B42^*N. If one (or both) of your opponents is a passed hand, assume that player has fewer than 12 HCP. If that player turns up with 10 HCP early on, play the partner for any missing queen, king, or ace.|
